There are a number of different types of cookies, however, our website uses:Functionality - Our Company uses these cookies so that we recognize you on our website and remember your previously selected Required - Advertising - Our Company uses these cookies to collect information about your visit to our website, the content you viewed, the links you followed and information about your browser, device, and your IP Our Company sometimes shares some limited aspects of this data with third parties for advertising We may also share online data collected through cookies with our advertising This means that when you visit another website, you may be shown advertising based on your browsing patterns on our - How to manage cookies You can set your browser not to accept cookies, and the above website tells you how to remove cookie

came together to solve a problem in As we saw it, crypto was a wild and untamed There was no industry data or news aggregator—no crypto version of a Bloomberg There was no clean and consistent way of settling trades, no custody for digital asset storage, and no unified (and timely) path for Instead, there was With the right software, many of the issues we saw plaguing the industry could be We knew we were the team to build that software, so that’s exactly what we We’re the team that built Strix Leviathan Strix is an efficient and secure trading platform that uses algorithms to mitigate risk and After going live with it in April , Strix quickly became the industry’s most robust management We used it to operate a successful hedge fund, but because of SEC restrictions, access to these sophisticated tools remained out of reach for retail That didn’t sit right with We believe cryptocurrencies should be accessible to The industry provides a unique opportunity to invest in technology, and it has the potential to compound capital at rates unavailable in other asset That shouldn’t be reserved for the So in , we spun off a new company using our software and we called it Makara, the first ever for Makara is crypto investing decrypted With the Strix Leviathan platform at its core, Makara offers diversified baskets—curated and managed by our technology—that cover the spectrum of available digital It’s crypto on autopilot, automatically rebalancing baskets and shifting to the currencies that our sophisticated algorithms Makara provides an opportunity for anyone to invest in a basket of digital assets For as little as $50, you can invest in crypto in less than five There’s no prior knowledge required, either, since our approach takes the inscrutability out of We want you to I’m Stephanie King, founder of Kitchen & I’ve been dreaming of launching Kitchen & Market for years - a market offering meal kits along with a carefully curated selection of Think specialty market meets meal kit service with a touch of everyday We aim to provide a answer to that daily question: “what’s for dinner?” The doors were to swing open in And then the world turned upside So, we pivoted, we launched a delivery and meal kit service in Over the past year and a half, we have been perfecting recipes and learning, a But through it all, one thing has become incredibly We all still need No matter what, we need Now, more than ever, we need This current state has reignited my passion for bringing people together through good And now it s time, we are finally moving forward with our original dream - our very first store will open this fall in Pike Place We’re grateful to have a place at your table and we hope to bring a little joy to your kitchen every time you unpack one of our meal kits or stop in our store - whether it be for a gallon of milk, a little dinner inspiration, or a sweet Who We Are An essential part of the Kitchen & Market team is my daughter, Someday, when people ask her what she did when the pandemic struck during her senior year in high school, she’ll say she dove right into starting Kitchen & Market with her Hannah has done everything from web development and social media to helping with cooking and recipe She is the perfect partner and I m her biggest Over the past couple years, a few things have changed - Hannah has headed off to college (although remains a forever presence here at Kitchen & Market) and while the team has grown, one thing remains the same, we are committed to providing good food - food that we would all be proud to serve to our own friends and families - from our kitchen to Meet the Team Stay in touch! Fine Motor Skills | My First Five Years 6 Streams Cognitive Fine Motor Gross Motor Language Sensory Social & Emotional Why Streams Our App Our Experts Content Submission Blog Contact Us Fine Motor Skills Fine Motor Skills are the skills that develop following on from the progression of gross motor This is because fine motor skills require the strength and coordination of the gross motor muscles in order to operate smaller muscles in the body, such as hands, fingers and Fine Motor Skills – Hands and fingers Fine Motor Skills are the skills that develop following on from the progression of gross motor This is because fine motor skills require the strength and coordination of the gross motor muscles in order to operate smaller muscles in the body, such as hands, fingers and Fine motor skills present themselves as intricate, more defined actions that require manual dexterity such as picking things up between a finger and thumb, wriggling toes and even the manipulation of lips and For your child to learn to do things for themselves, they will need to learn to coordinate both their fine and gross motor You will be able to see this happening as your child uses toys as they steady themselves (using their gross motor skills) then grab at and manipulate the object (using their fine motor skills). They will become more precise and successful in their movements over time because as they say, practice makes What is a fine motor skill? Fine motor skills are small, detailed movements that involve using the tendons and cartilage in your wrists, hands, fingers and They are slight movements that we don’t give much thought However, they are complex and involve the coordination of the eyes, brain and muscles to allow us to develop movements such as holding, grasping, pinching and releasing small They are thought to be essential in supporting children’s overall learning and Fine motor skills allow us to carry out everyday tasks such as: Holding and manipulating objects Writing Drawing Cutting Playing Eating Dressing Taking care of our personal hygiene When do fine motor skills develop? Every child’s development is completely unique to them and as with all skills, they take time to progress and Fine motor skills grow upon established gross motor skills with development following a likely Starting at the inner body, large muscles develop first including core, head, neck, arms and legs and then development moves to the outer body with hands, fingers, feet and Therefore, it is important that your child has lots of opportunities to practice and develop their gross motor skills through play first of The pace at which fine motor skills develop is very individual, but some of the milestone’s children achieve follow a similar pattern of development as the muscle groups Some of these milestones include: Grasps objects with whole hand (Grasp Reflex) Opens and closes hand (Ulnar Palmer Grasp) Holds object between fingers and thumb (Radial Palmer Grasp) Grabs toys by opening and closing hand and extending fingers (Raking Grasp) Transfers object from hand to hand Plays and manipulates objects using fingers, palm and pad of thumb (Radial Digital Grasp) Picks things up with thumb and finger (Pincer Grasp) Stacks, turns and manipulates Mark making progresses to using thumb and fingers rather than Marks become more obvious (e.g., circles and lines). Eats and drinks without assistance Cuts snips using scissors Copies marks Independently dresses and undresses How to develop fine motor skills in a child? Making Marks Exploring the patterns that our fingers can make is crucial in developing fine motor Some ways you could do this at home include using shaving foam on the wall of the shower, exploring how yogurt moves around the table of their highchair, using a brush in a tray of dried rice, a stick in the mud whilst on a walk or chalk on the pavement When we talk about mark making, we don’t just mean using pens and paper, although this is great Independent activities Encouraging your child to be independent is a brilliant way to develop their fine motor Putting on their own coat, using their own spoon, brushing their hair and teeth and attempting to pour their own water all require the use of their fine muscles, brain and eyes, so are great ways to encourage this Building and constructing Stacking objects takes a lot of hand and eye coordination, planning and movements such as pushing and This sort of play can be done with traditional blocks, but children might find it more enjoyable to use household objects such as boxes, tubs, tubes, toilet rolls or Sand and water play Materials that move such as sand and water are brilliant for developing this The process of moving, containing and pouring the materials whilst using different utensils helps to develop fine motor You could do this sort of play during bath time and if you don’t have sand, you can use things such as dried rice or lentils in a tray Dough Dough is a wonderful resource for It encourage

Education – Enhance Health Explore Plans Education Why Enhance Health Contact Us (TTY ) Medicare An introduction to eligibility, coverage, and Medicare Advantage Whether you’re about to become eligible for Medicare or need a change to your policy, it’s helpful to know the basics to make informed decisions about your With over million Americans enrolled , Medicare is the largest health insurance program in the , intended for people years and older or living with a qualifying disability or Renal Medicare Advantage provides “all-in-one” Medicare Also known as Part C, MA combines the essential components of Part A (hospital insurance) and Part B (medical and outpatient insurance), adding a few other types of insurance to provide full coverage for nearly % of all Medicare beneficiaries . To learn more about enrollment and eligibility into Medicare Advantage, refer to these frequently asked questions (FAQs). The ABC’s of Medicare Medicare is comprised of four different parts: A, B, C & Parts A and B are sometimes referred to as Original Medicare and are managed by the Federal Parts C and D are offered by private insurance companies that contract directly with Part A Hospital Insurance Helps cover: inpatient care in hospitals skilled nursing facility care hospice care home health care Part B Medical Insurance Helps cover: Services from doctors and other health care providers Outpatient care Home health care Durable medical equipment (like wheelchairs, walkers, hospital beds, and other equipment) Many preventive services (like screenings, shots or vaccines, and yearly “Wellness” visits) Part C Medicare Advantage Also known as Medicare Advantage , Part C is an alternative to traditional Medicare Coverage normally includes all of Parts A and B, a prescription drug plan (Part D), and, depending on your choice of a Medicare Advantage plan, other possible benefits such as Dental, Vision, and Part C is administered by private insurance companies that collect your Medicare payment from the federal Part D Drug coverage Helps cover: the cost of prescription drugs (including many recommended shots or vaccines). You join a Medicare drug plan in addition to Original Medicare , or you get it by joining a Medicare Advantage Plan with drug Plans that offer Medicare drug coverage are run by private insurance companies that follow rules set by Medicare Advantage FAQs Answers to commonly asked questions concerning Medicare Advantage Introduction What are the benefits of Medicare Advantage? With Medicare Advantage, you receive the same coverage you would get with Traditional Medicare (Parts A and B) alongside other types of coverage, like vision, hearing, and If you have a chronic illness, you can even choose a Medicare Advantage plan created specifically with your illness in mind, making it easier to receive ongoing What does Medicare Advantage cover? By law, Medicare Advantage will always cover the same services as Traditional Medicare, with the exception of hospice That means Medicare Advantage includes hospital care, medical care, outpatient care, prescription drug, vision, dental, and hearing Depending on the provider you choose, it can also come with additional benefits, like gym memberships and discounts, reimbursements for transportation to doctors’ appointments, and coverage for What are the different Medicare Advantage plans? The most common Medicare Advantage plans are Health Maintenance Organization (HMO) plans, Preferred Provider Organization (PPO) plans, Private (PFFS) plans, and Special Needs Plans (SNPs). Less common are HMO (HMOPOS) plans and Medical Savings Account (MSA) Enrollment When can I enroll in Medicare Advantage? It depends on your If you’re eligible based on age, the earliest you can enroll in Medicare Advantage is 3 months before you turn , which marks the start of your initial enrollment Your initial enrollment period lasts for 7 months, after which you may incur late fees or experience wait times while What is an annual election period? Medicare’s annual election period (or annual enrollment period) is when those who aren’t enrolled in Medicare can join, and anyone already enrolled can make changes to their It lasts from October to December 7 each What is an open enrollment period? If you’re already enrolled in Medicare Advantage, open enrollment is another opportunity to make a change to your It lasts from January 1 to March each What is a special enrollment period? A special enrollment period is when you can sign up for Medicare Advantage after your initial enrollment period or outside of the annual election period due to certain qualifying life These include losing health coverage, moving, getting married, having a baby, or adopting a child, or being for Medicaid or What are qualifying life events? Qualifying life events are occasions that trigger special enrollment periods, allowing you to sign up for Medicare outside of the annual election They include losing health coverage, moving, getting marri

Science - Restore Energy Balance to Treat Metabolic Disorders Skip to content Restoring Energy Homeostasis to Treat Severe Metabolic Disorders OrsoBio’s development programs address high unmet medical need in patients with severe metabolic disorders, including type 2 diabetes, severe hypertriglyceridemia, and congenital and acquired Our programs address the root cause of organ dysfunction by modulating fundamental metabolic pathways with four highly targeted and complementary mechanisms: 0 M Type 2 diabetes patients worldwide 0 x Risk of pancreatitis in severe hypertriglyceridemia < 0 % Of lipodystrophy patients on approved therapies due to limited efficacy, cost, and or side effects 1 Increased fatty acid oxidation in cardiac muscle (ACC2), plus beneficial effects on plasma lipids (LXR, protonophores) 2 Hepatic DNL inhibition (LXR, protonophores), increased fatty acid oxidation (ACC2, protonophores), increased NAD+ synthesis, and improved mitochondrial function (ACMSD) 3 Increased NAD+ synthesis and improved mitochondrial function in kidneys (ACMSD) 4 Increased fatty acid oxidation in skeletal muscle (ACC2) Each of our programs modulates central aspects of cellular energetics in key, organs PROGRAM OVERVIEW ACC2 Inhibitor (TLC-3595) Carboxylase 2 (ACC2) regulates oxidation of fatty acids by controlling their entry into mitochondria is a potent, oral, selective, allosteric inhibitor of ACC2 that has completed a Phase 1 study In preclinical studies, increased fatty acid oxidation, reduced ectopic lipid accumulation in muscle, liver and heart, and improved insulin sensitivity, making it an attractive therapeutic option for addressing insulin resistance in patients with type 2 diabetes Read More PROGRAM OVERVIEW LXR Inverse Agonist (TLC-2716) Liver X Receptor (LXR) is the master regulator of cholesterol homeostasis and de novo lipogenesis (DNL) is a inhibitor of LXR that is currently in Phase 1 development In preclinical studies, reduced hepatic steatosis and plasma triglycerides and cholesterol, supporting its development as a potential oral therapy for patients with severe dyslipidemias Read More Read More PROGRAM OVERVIEW Mitochondrial Protonophores (TLC-6740, ) By increasing energy expenditure, mitochondrial protonophores have broad metabolic benefits, including AMPK activation, DNL inhibition, and increased fatty acid oxidation and TCA cycle flux is a novel, mitochondrial protonophore designed to have a wide therapeutic index due to active hepatic uptake and reduced plasma exposure is a mitochondrial protonophore that has an enhanced safety margin In preclinical models, and have demonstrated consistent metabolic benefits, including weight loss and improved liver and plasma triglycerides and insulin sensitivity, without evidence of excessive systemic uncoupling Both and have potential to treat a broad range of metabolic disorders, including lipodystrophies, diabetes, and obesity Read More PROGRAM OVERVIEW ACMSD Inhibition ACMSD (Aminocarboxymuconate Semialdehyde Decarboxylase) is a key enzyme involved in the de novo synthesis of NAD+, which is critical to mitochondrial function via maintenance of cellular redox state, signaling, and overall energy homeostasis ACMSD is highly expressed in liver and kidney and NAD+ is reduced in patients with advanced liver and kidney disease In preclinical studies, ACMSD inhibition led to increased NAD+ synthesis, improved mitochondrial function, and protected against liver and kidney injury Read More Publications November 1, Enhanced lipogenesis associated with a GCKR variant (rs1260326) is effectively suppressed by , a novel, LXR inverse agonist in steatotic human liver organoids (AASLD , Abstract #4210) Read More November 1, Evaluation of the safety and pharmacokinetic effects of the oral, (ACC2) inhibitor in healthy volunteers (AASLD , Abstract #3677) Read More November 1, , a potent mitochondrial protonophore, has multiple metabolic benefits in preclinical models (AASLD , Abstract #2551) Read More November 1, , a potent, , inverse agonist of the liver X receptor (LXR), demonstrates profound reductions in hepatic and plasma lipids in dysmetabolic rodent models (AASLD , Abstract #2532) Read More November 1, Enhancement of de novo NAD+ biosynthesis by novel ACMSD inhibitors improves mitochondrial function in human liver organoid models of steatohepatitis (AASLD , Abstract #2441) Read More OrsoBio is developing novel therapies to treat patients with severe metabolic disorders, including diabetes, severe dyslipidemias, Those that havenât made the shift have struggled to acquire, retain, and delight customers (slow growth, missing ARR targets, long sales cycles, high CAC). Salesforce & Hubspot) are not designed to ingest times series data, which is the type of product data that you need to generate meaningful insights about your users (eg. DAU increased by %). Vasowatch - Home Home Deploying decision support technology for the clinical care team to improve outcomes for all mothers Maternal morbidity and mortality caused by postpartum hemorrhage is preventable Vasowatch assesses risk for postpartum hemorrhage (PPH) accurately and consistently, enabling improved obstetric outcomes for all Our wearable device continuously monitors optical data during labor and delivery to objectively assess the mother s current PPH risk, communicating a change to the clinical care The clinical care team can prepare for and provide prompt, appropriate PPH treatment, saving lives and minimizing costly Maternal health needs global attention Maternal mortality is unacceptably high PPH is a leading cause of maternal mortality PPH prevalence is significant US deaths births % ,000 mothers year Global ,000 year % 7,000,000 mothers year Vasowatch enables a proactive response to improve maternal outcomes Current practices for detecting postpartum hemorrhage rely on judgement calls, which are inaccurate and subjective, or vitals signs, which are lagging indicators for Existing risk factor assessments are also unreliable and do not predict % of postpartum hemorrhage incidents in "low risk" Vasowatch is changing the landscape of maternal risk assessment by identifying patients at risk up to minutes ahead of ​ Monitors continuously Optical sensors continuously monitor the maternal compensatory reserve for risk assessment Alerts care team Algorithm objectively alerts clinical care team to postpartum hemorrhage risk Enables early, effective intervention Improved risk assessment enables earlier and appropriate PPH intervention Bringing obstetric care into the century Better risk assessment enables earlier and consistent PPH intervention for this treatable condition, reducing maternal morbidity and ​ Our vision is to develop technology to support the clinical care team in improving outcomes and delivering a higher quality, lower cost birth experience to all Meet Our Team Founding team grounded in clinical care and technology development STEFANIE MODRI , University of Pennsylvania OB nurse & educator CHRISTINE ROHAN CEO Digital health and F100 executive JAMES WEIMER , University of Pennsylvania Computer scientist & medical device developer Contact Us Grays Ferry Ave, Philadelphia PA ​ Powered by Create your own unique Contact More Use tab to navigate through the menu The only patented , disposable, electrocautery device that can cauterize deep tissue through a guide SAFE FAST EFFECTIVE Millions of solid organ biopsy procedures are performed every year that sometimes result in adverse events related to the guide needle size used for collecting tissue samples and for high risk patients (those with blood disorders, or on anticoagulation medication). Additionally, it is impossible to predict and easily detect which patients may bleed, develop hematomas, or hemorrhage Currently, numerous medication and procedural techniques are attempted in order to minimalize post procedure These techniques include eliminating or administering new medications, using hemostatic agents to plug the biopsy channel, and holding patients in the recovery area with pressure bandages for several hours, or even However, none of these techniques are completely effective as hemorrhage requiring blood transfusions and surgical repair, and occasionally death, still Traditional techniques can result in hemorrhaging after biopsies requiring unnecessary: CT Scans Open Surgical Repair Two Week Patient Recovery Time Blood Transfusions
